Exercise 1: Exploratory Data Analysis

  1. Visualize the distribution of score in the dataframe evals.
ggplot(data = evals,
       mapping = aes(x = score)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

evals %>%
  summarise(
    evals_mean = mean(score),
    evals_median = median(score),
    evals_min = min(score)
  )
##   evals_mean evals_median evals_min
## 1    4.17473          4.3       2.3

The data is skewed towards the highest score, with the average score being 4.17 out of 5. This tells us that students generally liked their classes. Additionally, the ;lowest score a student provided was 2.3, only just under half of the maximum possible score, again indicating the classes were well liked.I think this is to be expected as students can pick their courses at university so are more likely to enjoy what they take.

Exercise 2: Simple Linear regression with a numerical predictor

  1. Fit a linear model called score_bty_fit to predict average professor evaluation score from average beauty rating (bty_avg). Print the regression output using tidy().
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
score_bty_fit <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  fit(score ~ bty_avg, data = evals)
# remove eval = FALSE from the code chunk options after filling in the blanks
tidy(score_bty_fit)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   3.88      0.0761     51.0  1.56e-191
## 2 bty_avg       0.0666    0.0163      4.09 5.08e-  5

score = 3.88 + 0.067 x bty_avg

  1. Plot the data again using geom_jitter(), and add the regression line.
ggplot(data = evals,
       mapping = aes(
         x = score, y = bty_avg
       )) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  1. Interpret the slope of the linear model in context of the data.

People tend to score better looking professors higher

  1. Interpret the intercept of the linear model in context of the data. Comment on whether or not the intercept makes sense in this context.

the intercept is 3.88 in this model.this means that someone with the lowest score would on average have a beauty rating of 3.88.
